Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[For a description of the Jalal-Abad region, read more at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jalal-Abad_Region: "Wheat, fruit, vegetables, maize, nuts, tobacco, and silk-worm cocoons are grown in the region. The region also has a few textile plants and hydroelectric stations. Minerals, natural gas, coal, metals, and oil can be found here, notably around the town of Kochkor-Ata, which is home to small-scale oil industry. Most of the extraction of minerals, natural gas, coal, metals, and oil of the Soviet era has ceased.... Except for the small fringes of the Fergana Valley, Jalal-Abad region is a land of mountains." Aksy is a raion (district) of Jalal-Abad region in western Kyrgyzstan. For a map and description, see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aksy_District.

From the very brief description, this was a typical outbreak arising from the butchering of an animal dying of anthrax and the meat given to neighbours' families. It is very fortunate that there were no fatal gastroenteric cases of anthrax, only cutaneous cases from handling the meat. The authorities appear to be on top of it by capping the cattle graves (2) with concrete. The district abuts the Fergana valley of Uzbekistan, which has a long history of livestock anthrax. Being at constant risk, it is a pity that the Kyrgyz districts bordering Fergana do not routinely vaccinate their cattle, but as outbreaks can be sporadic, the reluctance of the cattle owners is understandable. - Mod.MHJ

HealthMap/ProMED map of Jalal-Abad region, Kyrgyzstan: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8660105,59892]
